## Platform Portability

### What is identical on both platforms

  dial("tcp!host!port", nil, nil, nil)
  tlsClient(fd, &conn)
  threadspawn(fd[3], cmd, argv)
  threadpostmountsrv(...)
  lib9p, libbio, libthread
  mk + mkfile

### What differs: port.c (~50 lines)

  char *homedir(void)
  {
      char *h;
      if((h = getenv("home")) != nil) return h;
      if((h = getenv("HOME")) != nil) return h;
      return smprint("/usr/%s", getuser());
  }

  char *configpath(char *name)   /* ~/lib/9ai/<name> */
  {
      return smprint("%s/lib/9ai/%s", homedir(), name);
  }

Plan 9 conventions throughout: ~/lib/9ai/, not ~/.config/.

### ioproc

Used only for iodial().  Synchronous Brdline() inside the agent proc is safe
because agent and 9P server run in separate procs.

### Plan 9-specific benefits

  rfork(RFCNAMEG): exec children get a clean namespace
  werrstr/rerrstr: no errno, no strerror
  Factotum (v2): OAuth token stored in factotum instead of ~/lib/9ai/token

