## Conversation History

### In-memory representation

  typedef struct Block Block;
  struct Block {
      int   type;        /* BlockText, BlockThinking, BlockToolCall, BlockToolResult */
      char *text;
      char *tool_id;     /* BlockToolCall, BlockToolResult */
      char *tool_name;   /* BlockToolCall */
      char *tool_input;  /* BlockToolCall: accumulated JSON */
      int   is_error;    /* BlockToolResult */
      Block *next;
  };

  typedef struct Msg Msg;
  struct Msg {
      int    role;       /* RoleUser, RoleAssistant, RoleTool */
      Block *content;
      ulong  ts;
      Msg   *next;
  };

Content blocks are necessary to correctly serialise multi-block assistant
messages for the Anthropic API (a single turn can have thinking + text +
tool_use blocks in sequence).

### Orphaned tool call invariant

Before sending a new user message, check: if the last assistant message has
a tool_use block with no following tool_result, insert a synthetic error result:
  role:toolResult, tool_id:<id>, is_error:true, text:"aborted"

Prevents 400 errors after aborted turns.  ~30 lines of C.

### Reconstruction from session file

On /session/load, the agent proc scans forward through the session file:
  prompt record       → new RoleUser message with BlockText
  text records        → concatenate into RoleAssistant BlockText
  thinking records    → RoleAssistant BlockThinking (not sent to API)
  tool_start record   → RoleAssistant BlockToolCall (accumulate argv into JSON)
  tool_end record     → RoleUser message with BlockToolResult
  model record        → update current model name

The argv fields from tool_start are re-joined into a JSON array for
BlockToolCall.tool_input so the API request builder can serialise them.

